In React, if you want to **clone an element**, you use the built‑in helper `React.cloneElement()`. This lets you take an existing element and create a new one with additional props or children.

---

## 🔹 Basic Example
```jsx
import React from "react";

function App() {
  const originalDiv = <div className="box">Original</div>;

  const clonedDiv = React.cloneElement(originalDiv, {
    className: "box cloned",
    children: "Cloned"
  });

  return (
    <div>
      {originalDiv}
      {clonedDiv}
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

**Output:**
```
<div class="box">Original</div>
<div class="box cloned">Cloned</div>
```

---

## 🔹 Adding Props Dynamically
```jsx
function Button({ children }) {
  return <button>{children}</button>;
}

function App() {
  const btn = <Button>Click me</Button>;

  const clonedBtn = React.cloneElement(btn, { style: { color: "red" } });

  return (
    <>
      {btn}
      {clonedBtn}
    </>
  );
}
```

👉 The cloned button has the same structure but with extra props (`style`).

---

## ⚖️ Key Points
- `React.cloneElement(element, props, children)`:
  - `element`: the React element you want to clone.
  - `props`: new props to merge with the original.
  - `children`: optional new children to replace the original ones.
- Useful when you want to **inject props** into children passed to a component.

---

✨ So: `React.cloneElement` is the standard way to duplicate and modify existing React elements.  

